    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "# Save applications with Airtable and Telegram\n\n**Pattern:** Form Intake · **Level:** Core · **Trigger:** Form\n\n## What it does\nSave applications with Airtable and Telegram. It starts from a hosted form submission.\n\n## Why it exists\nManual inbox triage is slow and error-prone; this workflow makes the process repeatable, monitored and hands-off, with failures surfaced instead of silently lost.\n\n## Main flow\nNew Email Form Submission → Keep Valid Emails → Prepare Approval Packet → Request Approval via Slack → Hold for Decision → Approved? → Apply Approved Change (Airtable) → …\n\n## Use it for\n- Teams that want to form intake without manual effort\n- Anyone automating inbox triage in marketing\n- Replacing a fragile manual process with a reliable workflow\n\n## You get\n- Saves hours of manual work each week\n- Responds in seconds\n- Scales without extra headcount\n\n## Before first run\nConnect credentials: Airtable PAT; Slack OAuth2; Telegram bot token.\nFollow the color key: 🟦 entry · 🟪 AI · 🟫 actions · ⬜ utilities · 🟩 outputs · 🟥 error rail.\nEach node has its own doc card underneath — read those before editing.",
        "width": 480,
        "height": 900
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        -830,
        80
      ],
      "id": "a2d52cfe-d4b7-7911-b729-da4834839d03",
      "name": "📘 Workflow Overview"
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## 🛟 Error handling & retries\n\nExternal calls retry **3× with 2s backoff**. Anything still failing exits through its node's error output into the red error rail → context is captured and the on-call channel is alerted. Set an n8n **Error Workflow** in settings as the final safety net.",
        "width": 360,
        "height": 260,
        "color": 3
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        -230,
        -260
      ],
      "id": "584a8792-282e-c3be-ff9d-e79149b68fd3",
      "name": "🛟 Error handling & retries"
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## ⏱ Rate limiting\n\nWork is batched and spaced with Wait so provider quotas aren't tripped. If you hit 429s, lower the batch size or raise the wait — throughput drops, reliability rises.",
        "width": 360,
        "height": 260,
        "color": 1
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        190,
        -260
      ],
      "id": "3c89cc47-8467-ec1d-328d-4ee5328fb8ce",
      "name": "⏱ Rate limiting"
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## 🙋 Human in the loop\n\nThe workflow pauses at the Wait node until a human posts a decision to the resume URL (included in the approval message). Approve → the action executes; anything else → recorded as declined. No timeout is set by default — add one under the Wait node's options if approvals go stale.",
        "width": 360,
        "height": 260,
        "color": 1
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        610,
        -260
      ],
      "id": "53427424-0a7c-8fad-a963-8362188e9dc9",
      "name": "🙋 Human in the loop"
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## 🛠 Customize me\n\nQuick wins: point the data nodes at your own accounts (see 🔑 lines on each card), adjust the trigger cadence, and tune thresholds/labels to your inbox triage process. Every node card explains its role — safe to extend at any marked branch.",
        "width": 360,
        "height": 260,
        "color": 4
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        1030,
